# Packaging `{{APP_NAME}}` — the OCI + signature path

`./oci/build-oci.sh` takes your built app all the way to a **signed, scanned OCI bundle**,
entirely off-device. It is the authoring-side half of the PocketForge app packaging path
(E8); the on-device launch+verify is a separate, owner-gated hardware phase.

```
build/{{APP_SLUG}}.arm64 + launch + app.toml
        │
        ▼   ./oci/build-oci.sh
  mmdebstrap --format=tar  ─►  umoci OCI image-layout  ─►  cosign sign-by-DIGEST  ─►  oci.sig
                               syft SBOM  ─►  sbom.spdx.json    minisign  ─►  app.toml.sig
                               grype vs pinned DB  ─►  grype-report.json   (SEPARATE, non-blocking)
        │
        ▼   off-device VERIFY (the exact checks the on-device supervisor will run)
  dist/{{APP_SLUG}}/  ─  app.toml, app.toml.sig, oci/, oci.sig, sbom.spdx.json, grype-report.json, slice.conf
```

## Run it

```sh
./build.sh                 # produce build/{{APP_SLUG}}.arm64 first
./oci/build-oci.sh         # dev-sign + scan + verify   (needs docker + network on first run)
```

First run builds a **hermetic pinned toolchain image** (`oci/Dockerfile.pack` + `oci/pins-pack.env`:
mmdebstrap, umoci, cosign, syft, grype, minisign — each at a sha256-pinned version) and
registers qemu-arm64 binfmt, so packaging is reproducible off any docker host and never
depends on what happens to be installed. **Never apt/pip into a container** — the recipe is the
Dockerfile; bump a tool by editing `oci/pins-pack.env` on its own PR.

## The two-signature bundle

| sibling | signer | over what |
|---|---|---|
| `app.toml.sig` | **minisign** (Ed25519) | `app.toml` — the descriptor |
| `oci.sig` | **cosign** (sigstore bundle) | `oci/index.json` — the content-addressed **Merkle root** of the OCI image-layout |

`oci.sig` signs the image **BY DIGEST**: `index.json` commits to the manifest by `sha256:…`,
which commits to the config and every layer by digest, and every blob is stored under
`oci/blobs/sha256/<its-digest>`. So a valid signature over `index.json` + content-addressed
load is a signature over the **entire image** — tampering any blob changes a digest the
signature commits to. `dist/{{APP_SLUG}}/oci.digest` records the signed image digest.

The **OCI is addressed by digest and written under `dist/` (gitignored) — never commit it to
git.** Publishing the bundle by digest to a distribution channel is a separate concern (E8.4).

## Signing keys — dev vs release (the honest boundary)

- `--dev` (default): signs with a **locally-generated dev/test keypair** (`dist/keys/`) to
  PROVE the mechanism end-to-end off-device. **This is not release signing.**
- `--release-keys --minisign-key … --cosign-key …`: signs with real keys you supply.

The **real PocketForge release keys are trust-tier / CI-OIDC-only** and are not readable by
an author (or an agent). First-party apps are release-signed by the image repo's
`sign-and-scan` CI, which assumes the signing role via GitHub OIDC in a protected environment.
Your dev-signed bundle proves the shape that CI's release-signed bundle will have.

## Why grype is decoupled and non-blocking

A CVE is a fresh fact about the world — a new one lands days after a byte-identical build.
Gating packaging on it would couple artifact identity to a moving external feed. So grype runs
against a **pinned DB snapshot**, writes `grype-report.json`, and **always succeeds**; acting on
findings is a separate policy decision, never a packaging-time hard-fail.
